    "content": "The Defense Priorities think tank, headquartered in Washington, D.C., released a new report urging the United States to cease its airstrike campaign in Somalia. The report concludes that the military strikes have not significantly weakened militant groups and may instead fuel recruitment and local grievances.\n\nAccording to the report, airstrikes have caused civilian casualties that undermine trust in the Somali government and its international partners. It points to data showing that while the number of strikes increased in recent years, the terrorist threat has not diminished proportionally.\n\nThe report recommends shifting focus to diplomatic engagement and supporting Somali-led security forces with training and equipment rather than direct military action. It also suggests that the U.S. should work with regional actors to address underlying political and economic drivers of conflict.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this report adds to growing debate about the effectiveness of military intervention in their homeland. Many diaspora members have expressed concern about civilian harm and lack of oversight. The findings may influence discussions among policymakers and advocacy groups seeking a more sustainable approach to peace.\n\nThe call to end airstrikes aligns with similar appeals from humanitarian organizations and some Somali officials. However, the U.S. military has maintained that strikes are necessary to disrupt terrorist networks and protect American forces.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/warbixin-mareykan-ah-oo-ku-baaqday-in-la-soo-afjaro-duqeymaha-soomaaliya/423849/",
